# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: manager-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Elections to the Baseball Hall of Fame for 2024 were conducted according to the rules most recently amended in 2022.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] As in the past, the Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA) voted by mail to select from a ballot of recently retired players, with the results announced on January 23.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Three candidates were inducted by BBWAA: Adrián Beltré, Todd Helton, and Joe Mauer.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Beltré and Mauer were inducted in their first year of eligibility; Helton was in his sixth year of eligibility.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The Contemporary Baseball Era Committee met on December 3, 2023 at the Winter Meetings to consider the election of eight managers, executives or umpires who made their greatest impact on the game since 1980.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Manager Jim Leyland was elected by the committee.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Inductees were honored in a ceremony at the Clark Sports Center on Sunday, July 21, 2024.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The list of players appearing on the BBWAA ballot was released on November 20, 2023.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] There were 14 players carried over from the 2023 ballot, who garnered at least 5% of the vote and were still eligible for election, as well as 12 players whose last major league appearance was in 2018, played at least 10 seasons of Major League Baseball, and were chosen by a screening committee.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] This was the final ballot for Gary Sheffield.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] A total of 385 ballots were cast, with 289 votes needed to reach the 75% threshold for election.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] A total of 2,696 votes were cast for individual players, an average of 7 votes per ballot.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Players who met first-year eligibility requirements but were not selected by the screening committee for inclusion on the ballot were: Matt Belisle, Gregor Blanco, Blaine Boyer, Santiago Casilla, Brett Cecil, Jorge de la Rosa, Brian Duensing, A.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The Contemporary Baseball Era Committee met on December 3 at the Winter Meetings to consider the election of eight managers, executives or umpires who have made their greatest impact on the game since 1980.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The final ballot was announced on October 19, 2023.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The eight Contemporary Baseball Era manager/executive/umpire finalists were selected by the BBWAA-appointed Historical Overview Committee from all eligible candidates whose most significant career impact was realized since 1980.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] All candidates must not be on Baseball’s Ineligible List.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Frick Award is presented annually to a broadcaster for "major contributions to baseball" and has been presented annually since 1978.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The 2024 award will be a composite ballot of local and national voices.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] On December 6, 2023, the Hall of Fame announced that Joe Castiglione won the Frick Award.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The BBWAA Career Excellence Award honors a baseball writer (or writers) "for meritorious contributions to baseball writing" and is presented during Hall of Fame Weekend by that year's President of the Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA).
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The award is voted upon annually by the BBWAA.
[src:manager-baseball/2024-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] On December 5, 2023, the Hall announced Gerry Fraley (1954–2019)—a sportswriter for several publications including *The Dallas Morning News* and *The Sporting News*—as the recipient of the 2024 BBWAA Career Excellence Award.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Born in Iowa, Hinch attended Midwest City High School in Oklahoma, and then Stanford University, where he played college baseball for the Cardinal.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In the 1996 MLB draft, the Athletics selected him in the third round, and he appeared in 350 games over seven major league seasons.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Following his playing career, Hinch managed the Arizona Diamondbacks from May 2009 to July 2010, and became vice president of professional scouting for the San Diego Padres from September 2010 to August 2014.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch joined the Houston Astros as manager from 2015 through 2019, guiding the club through one of the most successful periods in franchise history.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] They won the 2017 World Series, two American League (AL) pennants, and over 100 regular season games each from 2017 to 2019, including a club-record 107 in the latter.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Due to being implicated in the Astros' sign stealing scandal the following year, Hinch was suspended by MLB for one year and fired by the team.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Prior to the 2021 season, the Tigers hired Hinch as manager, and he guided the club to their next playoff appearance in 2024.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch lived in Nashua, Iowa, until he was eight, when he moved to Oklahoma.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He is a 1992 graduate of Midwest City High School in Midwest City, Oklahoma, where, as a senior, he was the 1992 National Gatorade Player of the Year in baseball.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He was drafted in the second round of the Major League Baseball draft but elected to attend Stanford University, where he was a third-round pick after his junior year in 1995.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He decided to return to school and was again a third-round pick as a senior in 1996.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] At Stanford he joined Delta Tau Delta International Fraternity.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch won a bronze medal for the United States at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics and was named to the 1998 Topps All-Star Rookie Team.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch is married to his wife, Erin Hinch, with two daughters Haley and Kaitlin.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch was selected by the Oakland Athletics in the third round of the 1996 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He signed with the Athletics in June 1996.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He debuted with the Athletics in 1998 and remained with the team through the 2000 season.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch was released by the Royals after the 2002 season.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He signed as a minor league free agent with the Cleveland Indians, but was purchased by the Detroit Tigers from the Indians in March 2003.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He signed with the Philadelphia Phillies for the 2004 season, splitting the year between the majors and Triple-A.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He spent all of 2005 with the Phillies' Triple-A affiliate before retiring.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In an eight-season major league career, Hinch had a .219 batting average with 32 home runs and 112 runs batted in in 350 games.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] After the 2005 season, the Arizona Diamondbacks hired Hinch as their manager of minor league operations.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Even while playing, he was planning his post-playing career.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He went so far as to go to the 2003 general manager's winter meetings to look for future job opportunities and contacts.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In July 2006, Baseball America named him one of baseball's "10 to watch" in the next 10 years for his promise as a farm director and future general manager.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In August 2006, the Diamondbacks named Hinch director of player development.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch was named manager of the Arizona Diamondbacks on May 8, 2009, replacing Bob Melvin, despite never having managed or coached a team at any level.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] At age 34 years and 357 days, Hinch became the youngest person to be named manager of a Major League team since Eric Wedge (34 years, 275 days).
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch, along with general manager Josh Byrnes, was fired from the Diamondbacks on July 1, 2010, following a 31–48 start to the 2010 season.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Overall, Hinch compiled an 89–123 record in 212 games; his .420 winning percentage ranks as the lowest for a non-interim manager in Diamondbacks history.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] The San Diego Padres hired Hinch as vice president of professional scouting on September 21, 2010.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He reunited with Byrnes, who was the Padres' senior vice president of baseball operations and in 2011 would become their general manager.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch served as interim GM in 2014 along with Omar Minaya and Fred Uhlman, Jr.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He resigned from the position on August 5, 2014.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch was named manager of the Houston Astros on September 29, 2014, replacing Bo Porter, who had been fired on September 1, 2014.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In the 2015 season, Hinch led the Astros to an 86–76 record and a wild card berth.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] It was Houston's first playoff appearance since their 2005 World Series run.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In the Wild Card Game, the Astros defeated the New York Yankees in Yankee Stadium, 3–0, to advance to the American League Division Series (ALDS).
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch's Astros took a 2–1 ALDS lead over the Kansas City Royals.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In Game 4, the Astros led the Royals, 6–2, going into the 8th inning; however, the Royals came back to win, 9–6, and the Astros went on to lose Game 5 and the series.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Although their play improved during the season, the Astros finished 84–78 and did not qualify for the playoffs.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In 2017, the Astros achieved a club-record of 50 wins in 74 games and finished the regular season 101–61, winning their first AL West division title, first division title in 16 years, and first since joining the AL.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] The 2017 postseason began for the Astros with the ALDS at home.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch guided the team past the Boston Red Sox in four games, with his decision to have Justin Verlander pitch in relief in the deciding Game 4 receiving attention.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In the American League Championship Series (ALCS), he led the Astros against the Yankees in Houston's first League Championship Series (LCS) appearance in 12 years.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] After his team won the first two games at home, the Yankees rallied with three wins in New York, with Game 4's loss resulting from the bullpen giving up six combined runs in the 7th and 8th after Hinch removed pitcher Lance McCullers Jr after only six innings.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] With a pivotal Game 6 in Houston and Justin Verlander on the mound, the Astros won the game, 7–1.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In Game 7, he chose Charlie Morton as his starter.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Morton tossed five innings, and Hinch brought in McCullers to pitch the final four in relief as the Astros shutout the Yankees, 4–0.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] The Astros faced the Los Angeles Dodgers in the World Series and won in 7 games.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch deployed the same four starting pitchers as he had in the ALCS: Dallas Keuchel, Verlander, McCullers Jr, and Morton, though only McCullers and Morton received wins as two relievers, Chris Devenski and Joe Musgrove, were credited with the other two.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In Game 7, Morton pitched the final four innings as the Astros won, 5–1, to clinch their first-ever title.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] With the win, Hinch earned his 14th playoff victory as manager of the Astros, establishing a club record that eclipsed the 13 attained by Phil Garner.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] On August 30, 2018, the Astros signed Hinch to a four-year extension.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] On May 28, 2019, Hinch won his 500th game as manager.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] The Astros won a franchise-record 107 games during the regular season, but lost to the Washington Nationals 4 games to 3 in World Series.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] On January 13, 2020, during the offseason, Hinch and Jeff Luhnow, the team's general manager, were suspended one year for violating MLB policies in a sign stealing scandal in 2017.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] The investigation revealed that Hinch did not approve of the players using a replay monitor to decode signs, and even went as far as to wreck the monitor on at least two occasions.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] However, he admitted that he did not stop the practice or explicitly let it be known that he disapproved of it.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Baseball Commissioner Rob Manfred harshly criticized Hinch for not doing more to stop the scheme.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] According to Manfred, the manager is responsible for "ensuring that the players both understand the rules and adhere to them.” Manfred concluded that there was "no justification for Hinch's failure to act,” since Hinch was the players’ immediate supervisor.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] If Hinch commits further "material violations" of baseball rules, he will be permanently banned from baseball.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch fully expected to be suspended, but believed Manfred would only suspend him for a month at most.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] The year-long suspension was the second-most severe punishment in baseball history meted out to a manager for in-game misconduct.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Louis Browns manager Jack O'Connor, who was banned for life for trying to throw the 1910 American League batting title to Nap Lajoie by bribing the official scorer to change a hit on error to a hit in the final game of the season.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Boston Red Sox manager Alex Cora also received a year-long suspension for his role in the scandal for his actions as the Astros' bench coach.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] As of the end of the 2019 season, his .594 winning percentage was the highest in franchise history.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Hinch's suspension ended after the 2020 season.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] He was scheduled to interview for the managerial openings with the Detroit Tigers and Chicago White Sox.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] When the White Sox unexpectedly hired Tony La Russa, they issued a press release mistakenly bearing Hinch's facsimile signature, suggesting Hinch was the team's original choice until owner Jerry Reinsdorf intervened.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] On October 30, 2020, Hinch was named the manager of the Tigers, agreeing on a multi-year contract.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] In 2024, Hinch led the Tigers to a wild card berth on an 86–76 third-place finish in the AL Central division.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Left-hander Tarik Skubal emerged as the staff ace, winning the AL Triple Crown, the first Tiger do to so since Verlander in 2011.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] A 55–63 record shortly after the trade deadline did not advertise a playoff destiny after having dealt starter Jack Flaherty, outfielder Mark Canha, reliever Andrew Chafin, and catcher Carson Kelly.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Their playoff seeding juxtaposed them with the Houston Astros in the AL Wild Card Series (WCS).
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] As such, Hinch became the third manager in MLB history to face his former team whom he led to a World Series title in a postseason tournament.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] During the 2025 season, Hinch and the Tigers agreed to a long-term contract extension running through at least the 2027 season.
[src:manager-baseball/a-j-hinch] Against the Yankees on June 29, 2026, Hinch recorded his 1,000th victory as a manager.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Following the conclusion of his playing career, Boone was an analyst for ESPN's *Sunday Night Baseball* and *Baseball Tonight* from 2010 to 2017.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He began serving as the Yankees' manager in 2018, leading the team to the playoffs in seven of his eight seasons and one World Series appearance in 2024.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Aaron John Boone was born on March 9, 1973, in La Mesa, California.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone attended Villa Park High School in Villa Park, California.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He batted .423 with 22 stolen bases for the school's baseball team in his senior year, and was named the Century League's co-player of the year.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The California Angels selected Boone on the third day of the 1991 MLB draft, but he had no intention to sign a professional contract.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He attended the University of Southern California (USC) and played college baseball for the USC Trojans.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] In 1993, he played collegiate summer baseball for the Orleans Cardinals of the Cape Cod Baseball League, where he was named a league all-star and helped lead Orleans to the league championship.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Cincinnati Reds selected Boone in the third round of the 1994 MLB draft.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone made his MLB debut in June 1997, and was ejected from the game after being called out sliding into home.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On the last day of the 1998 season, the Reds started the only MLB infield composed of two sets of brothers: first baseman Stephen Larkin, second baseman Bret Boone, shortstop Barry Larkin, and third baseman Aaron Boone.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On September 22, 2002, Boone hit the last home run in Riverfront Stadium in the eighth inning of the Reds' 4–3 loss to the Philadelphia Phillies, a solo home run off reliever Dan Plesac.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone hit a career-high 26 home runs in 2002, playing in all 162 games.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Reds named Boone their team's most valuable player.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He appeared in the 2003 MLB All-Star Game.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The New York Yankees acquired Boone from the Reds for Brandon Claussen, Charlie Manning, and cash on July 31, 2003.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] In 54 games after the trade, he hit .254 with a .720 OPS, six home runs and 31 RBIs.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] During Game 7 of the 2003 American League Championship Series (ALCS), Boone hit a walk-off home run in the 11th inning, off Tim Wakefield, which gave the Yankees a 6–5 victory over the Boston Red Sox, thus prolonging the Curse of the Bambino.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The *New York Daily News* dubbed the play the "Curse of the Boonebino".
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] This home run was rated the ninth-best home run of all time on *Baseball Tonight*.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] In January 2004, Boone tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee during a pick-up basketball game.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The game violated the standard MLB player contract, which forbids taking part in off-season basketball, skiing, and surfing.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Yankees immediately hinted that they would terminate his contract.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Soon after trading for Alex Rodriguez to play third base, the Yankees released Boone on February 27, 2004.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone signed a two-year contract with the Cleveland Indians in June 2004.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He earned $600,000 for 2004, $3 million for the 2005 season, and a club option for the 2006 season worth $4.5 million.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] After missing the entire 2004 season, Boone played 154 games in 2005.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He batted .243 with 16 home runs and 60 RBIs.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Indians exercised an option on Boone's contract for the 2006 season.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] In his second season with Cleveland, he batted .251 with seven home runs.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On December 29, 2006, Boone signed a one-year contract with the Florida Marlins worth $925,000.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He batted .286 in 69 games for the Marlins in 2007.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On December 6, 2007, Boone signed a one-year, $1,000,000 contract with the Washington Nationals.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] In 104 games, Boone hit .241 with 6 home runs and 28 RBIs in 2008.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On December 18, 2008, Boone signed a one-year $750,000, plus incentives, deal with the Houston Astros.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He played in only 10 games in 2009, reaching base only once—on a hit by pitch—in 14 plate appearances.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] In March 2009, Boone underwent open-heart surgery to replace a bicuspid aortic valve, a condition that he has been aware of since childhood, but which routine tests indicated had recently worsened.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone stated that doctors told him he could play baseball when he recovered, but he was not sure if he would choose to do so.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone returned to baseball on August 10, when he began his rehabilitation with the Corpus Christi Hooks, the Astros' Double-A minor league affiliate.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He played five innings and was hitless in two plate appearances.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone stated after the game that his goal was to return to the major leagues by September 1, the date that major league rosters expand.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone was activated on September 1, and added to the Astros' expanded roster.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On September 2, Boone made his season debut, playing at first base and going 0 for 3.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On September 16, Boone stated that he was leaning towards retirement, and on October 4, he played his last game.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone served as a guest analyst for the MLB Network coverage of the 2009 ALCS between the New York Yankees and Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On February 23, 2010, Boone announced his retirement and that he would become an analyst for ESPN.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone appeared on *Monday Night Baseball* and for *Baseball Tonight*'s pregame show on Sunday night.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone called the 2014 and 2015 World Series for ESPN Radio with play-by-play announcer Dan Shulman.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Jessica Mendoza and he became color commentators on *Sunday Night Baseball* with Shulman in 2016.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone and Shulman continued to call World Series games for ESPN Radio through 2017.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] After the 2017 season, the Yankees decided not to retain Joe Girardi as their manager; they hired Boone to succeed him on December 4, 2017.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Yankees started the 2018 season with a 6–1 win against the Toronto Blue Jays on March 29, 2018.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On September 2, 2018, Boone was suspended for one game for making illegal contact with an umpire.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He finished his first season with a 100–62 record, good for second in the American League East, and led the Yankees to the wild card game against the Oakland Athletics, despite losing star outfielder and team leader Aaron Judge for two months with a wrist injury.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On October 3, 2018, the Yankees defeated the Athletics 7–2 to advance to the American League Division Series, giving Boone his first postseason win as a manager.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Boston Red Sox eliminated the New York Yankees three–games–to–one in the American League Division Series *en route* to a World Series victory.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Yankees started the 2019 season with a 7–2 win against the Baltimore Orioles on March 28, 2019.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On September 19, after winning against the Los Angeles Angels 9–1, the Yankees clinched the American League East, becoming AL East Division Champions for the first time since 2012 and also earning their 100th win.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone became the first manager in MLB history to have 100 or more wins in each of his first two seasons.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Yankees went on to lose to the Houston Astros in the American League Championship Series.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Following the 2019 season, Boone was named a finalist for American League Manager of the Year award.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He finished runner-up to Minnesota Twins manager, Rocco Baldelli.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the Yankees and the other 29 Major League Baseball teams only played a 60-game regular season.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Yankees started off the shortened season with a hot 16–6 start, but then lost 15 of their next 20 games, evening their record at 21–21.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Yankees swept the Cleveland Indians in a best-of-three wild card series to advance to the ALDS against the Tampa Bay Rays, but their struggles against the Rays continued, as they were eliminated in five games.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] During the 2021 season, the Yankees had what was called one of the "streakiest [teams] in recent memory.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Through July 4, the team struggled to a 41–41 record with half of the season left to play, then went on a 51–29 run to end the season at 92–70.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Between August 14 and 28, the Yankees won 13 consecutive games, tied for fifth-longest in franchise history.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Following the winning streak, the team stumbled, going 3–12 between August 28 and September 12, and finished tied for second in the American League East behind the Tampa Bay Rays, but lost the wild card game to the Boston Red Sox 6–2.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Following the season, Boone signed a three-year contract with the Yankees with a club option for 2025.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] In 2022, Boone was ejected from nine games.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] He was ejected four times more often than any other MLB manager.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Yankees were 64–28 in the first half of the season by the All-Star Game and potentially headed to 100 wins.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] They proceeded to win 35 of their next 70 games to finish with a 99–63 record and an AL East title.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] They earned home-field advantage in Games 1, 2, and 5 of the ALDS.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] They beat the Cleveland Guardians in five games, but got swept by the Houston Astros in the ALCS, marking Boone's fifth-straight playoff exit.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] MLB suspended Boone for one game on May 26, 2023, for his conduct towards umpires after his fourth ejection of the season, and second in four days, the prior day.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] As of June 9, Boone has the third-highest ejection rate in MLB history among managers, behind only Paul Richards and Frankie Frisch, and ahead of Earl Weaver, Bobby Cox, and Ron Gardenhire, managers who were all known for their proclivity for getting ejected.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On September 24, 2023, the Yankees were eliminated from playoff contention for the first time under Boone's management.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] On November 8, 2024, the Yankees exercised the 2025 option clause for Boone.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Before the 2025 regular season began, Boone and the Yankees agreed to a two-year contract extension through 2027.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] The Yankees finished second in the AL East with a 94–68 record, narrowly behind the Toronto Blue Jays, who held the tiebreaker.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] They advanced past the Boston Red Sox by winning the Wild Card Series 2–1.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] They would go on to lose the Division Series to the Toronto Blue Jays 3–1.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone is the son of former catcher and manager Bob Boone, the brother of All Star and four-time Gold Glove winner and current Texas Rangers hitting coach Bret Boone, the brother of former Cincinnati Reds minor leaguer Matt Boone, and the grandson of former major leaguer Ray Boone.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] As children, Aaron and Bret spent time in the Phillies clubhouse with fellow sons of other major league players, including Pete Rose Jr.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone is a descendant of pioneer Daniel Boone.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone is a fan of the Philadelphia Eagles football team.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone's wife, Laura Cover, was a *Playboy* Playmate (Miss October 1998).
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone lived in Scottsdale, Arizona until becoming Yankees manager, when he moved to Greenwich, Connecticut.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone and Cover have four children—two biological children and two adopted.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone had open-heart surgery in 2009 and had surgery to implant a pacemaker in March 2021.
[src:manager-baseball/aaron-boone] Boone was quoted as feeling "awesome" after being on the bench for two weeks following the procedure.
[src:manager-baseball/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:manager-baseball/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:manager-baseball/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:manager-baseball/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:manager-baseball/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:manager-baseball/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:manager-baseball/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss was born and raised in Wisconsin, where he attended St.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Mary's College (later part of Wyalusing Academy) in Prairie du Chien and the University of Wisconsin.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Mary's and then played in a semipro league where he caught the attention of Connie Mack.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss did not sign with Mack's team, but he attracted further major league interest after winning 19 games in 1900 for the Toledo Mud Hens.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss had another strong season for Toledo in 1901.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] After an offseason contract dispute between Joss, Toledo and Cleveland, he debuted with the Cleveland club in April 1902.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss led the league in shutouts that year.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] By 1905, Joss had completed the first of his four consecutive 20-win seasons.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Off the field, Joss worked as a newspaper sportswriter from 1906 until his death.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In 1908, he pitched a perfect game during a tight pennant race that saw Cleveland finish a half-game out of first place; it was the closest that Joss came to a World Series berth.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The 1910 season was his last, and Joss missed most of the year due to injury.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In April 1911, Joss became ill and he died the same month due to tuberculous meningitis.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He finished his career with 160 wins, 234 complete games, 45 shutouts and 920 strikeouts.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Addie Joss was born on April 12, 1880, in Woodland, Dodge County, Wisconsin.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] His parents Jacob and Theresa (née Staudenmeyer) were farmers; his father, a cheesemaker who was involved in local politics, had emigrated from Switzerland.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] A heavy drinker of alcohol, he died from liver complications in 1890, when Joss was 10 years old; Joss remained sober throughout his life as a result of his father's death.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss attended elementary school in Juneau and Portage and high school at Wayland Academy in Beaver Dam, Wisconsin.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] By age 16 he finished high school and began teaching himself.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He was offered a scholarship to attend St.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Mary's College (also known as Sacred Heart College) in Watertown, where he played on the school's baseball team.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He also attended the University of Wisconsin (now University of Wisconsin–Madison), where he studied engineering.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Officials in Watertown were impressed with the quality of play of St.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Mary's and put the team on a semipro circuit.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] During his time on the semipro circuit, Joss employed his unique pitching windup, which involved hiding the ball until the very last moment in his delivery.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Connie Mack also sent a scout to watch Joss and later offered the young pitcher a job playing on his Albany club in the Western League, which Joss declined.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In 1899, Joss played for a team in Oshkosh, earning $10 per week ($387 in today's dollars).
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] After player salaries were frozen by team owners, Joss joined the junior team in Manitowoc, which had been split into two teams, as a second baseman and was soon promoted to the senior squad, where he was developed into a pitcher.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He was seen by a scout for the Toledo Mud Hens and in 1900 accepted a position with the team for $75 per month ($2,903).
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] While in Ohio he was considered "the best amateur pitcher in the state." He started the Mud Hens' season opener on April 28 and earned the win in the team's 16–8 victory.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Midway through the 1901 season, the Boston Americans of the upstart American League offered $1,500 ($58,050) to Toledo to buy out Joss's contract.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Louis Cardinals of the National League (NL) matched Boston's offer; Toledo rejected both offers.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss continued to pitch for the Mud Hens and by the end of the 1901 season he had won 27 games and had 216 strikeouts (some sources say 25 games).
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] After the season ended, Joss returned to Wisconsin where he led Racine to the 1901 Wisconsin baseball state championship against Rube Waddell's Kenosha squad.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He also enrolled at Beloit College and played American football.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] It was reported that Joss had signed with the Brooklyn Dodgers of the National League as early as August 18 and received a $400 advance ($15,480), but Joss denied receiving any money.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Mud Hens owner Charles Stroebel stated that he had signed Joss and other Mud Hens players for the 1902 season on August 12 and that the Western League was under the protection of the National League through September 1901.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Before 1901 ended, the Cleveland Bronchos offered $500 ($19,350) to Toledo in exchange for Joss and manager Bob Gilks, who would be a scout for Cleveland.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Toledo and Joss agreed and Joss was now a member of the American League, which was paying a premium on baseball talent to rival the National League.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Dodgers owner Charles Ebbets invited Joss for a meeting, which Joss declined, and Joss let it be known that he had told Stroebel he would play for the Mud Hens for the 1902 season, and received a $150 ($5,582) advance in February 1902.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In March 1902, Joss signed with Cleveland.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] For not returning the entire advance, Joss was charged with a felony and Stroebel pursued legal action.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss made his major league debut with the Bronchos on April 26, and two days later he arrived in Toledo to turn himself in, accompanied by Bronchos majority owner Charles Somers, who was also American League vice president.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Stroebel also filed a civil suit against the Bronchos, stating that his business had been interfered with, but Stroebel agreed to withdraw his charges in July when he accepted Bronchos pitcher Jack Lundbom.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss made his major league debut with the Cleveland Bronchos (also known as the Bluebirds) against the St.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The Browns' Jesse Burkett hit a shallow pop fly in the direction of right fielder Zaza Harvey.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Home plate umpire Bob Caruthers ruled that Harvey did not make a clean catch, so Burkett was credited with a hit.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] (Harvey and witnesses said the ball never hit the ground.) Joss finished his major league debut with a one-hitter.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss compiled a 17–13 record and 2.77 ERA during his major league rookie season.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He led the American League with five shutouts.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] On October 11, 1902, Joss married Lillian Shinivar in Monroe, Michigan.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Shinivar was in attendance when Joss made his professional debut with the Mud Hens in 1900.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The couple had a son, Norman, and a daughter, Ruth.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Following the conclusion of the 1902 season, Joss was selected to the All-Americans, an all-star team from the American League who played exhibition games against their counterparts from the National League.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] To begin the 1903 season, the Cleveland organization changed the team's name to the "Naps" in honor of second baseman Nap Lajoie.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In Joss' second year, he went 18–13 and lowered his ERA from the season before to 2.19.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] His walks plus hits per inning pitched (WHIP) was an MLB-low 0.948.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] For the 1904 season, the 24-year-old Joss went 14–10 with a 1.59 ERA and did not give up a home run during the season.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Illness during the season reduced his starts.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He had his first of four 20-win seasons in 1905 as he ended the season with a 20–12 record and 2.01 ERA.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He finished with a career-high 132 strikeouts.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In 1906 his 1.72 ERA was third in the league and he finished with a 21–9 record and tied a career-high with nine shutouts.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] To begin the 1907 season, Joss won his first 10 starts.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He threw two one-hitters during the season, the first on September 4 against the Detroit Tigers and the second on September 25 versus the New York Highlanders.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] When teammate Heinie Berger threw his own one-hitter on September 26, it marked just the second time since 1900 that two pitchers from the same team had thrown back-to-back one-hitters.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss finished the season with career-bests in wins (finished 27–11) and 338+2⁄3 innings pitched.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] His win total tied with Doc White for highest in the American League and his WHIP was second-best (behind Cy Young) while both his complete game (34) and shutout (6) totals were third-best in the league.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Before the 1908 season started, the Naps' home field, League Park, was expanded by about 4,000 seats.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In what proved to be one of the tightest ever pitching duels in a perfect game, Joss took the mound for the Naps, while the White Sox pitcher was future Hall of Famer Ed Walsh.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Neither pitcher would give up an earned run in the 1–0 game.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Walsh, blistering through his own 39 win season, struck out 15 batters, gave up only one base on balls and allowed only four scattered hits by the Naps.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The Naps' Joe Birmingham scored the team's only run, which came in the third inning—the lone, unearned run scored as a result of a botched pickoff play and a wild pitch.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The tension in the ballpark was described by one writer as "a mouse working his way along the grandstand floor would have sounded like a shovel scraping over concrete." Joss, having faced the minimum 24 batters in the first eight innings, retired the first two batters in the top of the ninth.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss then faced White Sox pinch hitter John Anderson.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Anderson hit a line drive that could have resulted in a double had it not gone foul.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He then hit a ball to Naps third baseman Bill Bradley, which Bradley bobbled before throwing to first baseman George Stovall.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Stovall dug the ball out of the dirt to achieve the final out.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] With the win, Joss recorded the second ever perfect game in MLB's modern era.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He accomplished the feat with just 74 pitches, the lowest known pitch count ever achieved in a perfect game.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] After the game, Joss said, "I never could have done it without Larry Lajoie's and Stovall's fielding and without Birmingham's base running.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] For the season, Joss averaged 0.83 walks per nine innings, becoming one of 29 pitchers in MLB history to average less than one walk per nine innings.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] His season-ending WHIP of .806 is the fifth-lowest single-season mark in MLB history.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The Naps finished with a 90–64 record, a half-game behind Detroit.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] It was the closest Joss ever got to a World Series appearance.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] After amassing four consecutive 20-win seasons, Joss struggled in 1909 as a result of fatigue; by September he was shut down for the season.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss finished the year with a 14–13 record in 242+2⁄3 innings pitched and recorded a 1.71 ERA.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He finished fourth in the American League in ERA and third in WHIP (.944).
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss pitched a second no-hitter, on April 20, 1910, against the White Sox, becoming the first pitcher in MLB history to no-hit the same team twice, a feat not matched until Tim Lincecum of the San Francisco Giants no-hit the San Diego Padres in both 2013 and 2014.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In the second inning, the White Sox' Freddy Parent hit a ball toward third base.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Bill Bradley failed to field the ball cleanly and thus his throw to first base was not in time to get Parent out.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The initial ruling on the field was a base hit but it was later changed to an error.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss gave up two walks and recorded 10 assists.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He made just 13 appearances that season due to a torn ligament in his right elbow.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss made his last appearance of the season on July 25, and left the game in the fifth inning due to arm soreness.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In his final game, he allowed three runs on five hits and two walks with six strikeouts in a 4–0 loss.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In his final major league season, Joss finished with a 5–5 record in 107+1⁄3 innings.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] This marked the fifth time in Joss' nine years that the franchise finished with a losing record.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Of Joss' 160 major league wins, 45 were shutouts.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss' 1.89 career ERA is ranked second all-time (to Ed Walsh), while his 0.97 WHIP (walks and hits per inning pitched) is the lowest career WHIP in MLB history.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He finished with a 160–97 record, 234 complete games, and 920 strikeouts.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss' repertoire included a fastball, a "slow ball" (today known as a changeup), and an "extremely effective" curve.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Baseball historians Rob Neyer and Bill James ranked Joss' fastball third (1900–1904) and sixth (1905–1909) in the major leagues.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] George Moriarty explained that Joss had only one curveball because "he believed that with a few well mastered deliveries he could acquire great control and success with less strain on his arm." In an era filled with spitball pitchers, Joss achieved his success without ever altering the baseball.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Illness and injury accompanied Joss throughout much of his professional career.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In 1903, a high fever forced him to miss the last month of the season.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He contracted malaria in April 1904 and then missed several starts with a back injury in 1905.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss was concerned about supporting his family after his baseball career ended; many players of the day had little education and few marketable job skills beyond their abilities on the diamond.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] As sportswriter Franklin Lewis wrote, "Only a handful of players in the rough, stirring, early days of the major leagues arrived from campuses.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] And when they did, sometimes the shock was too great for them.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Some grizzled holdovers from the 1890s were around and they bore down heavily on the eardrums of the so-called college-boy set." Joss was hired as a sports columnist after the 1906 season for the *Toledo News-Bee*.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He also served as their Sunday sports editor.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] His writings proved so popular that sales of the paper increased and a special phone line was installed in his office to field the large volume of calls he received from fans.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The increased popularity gave him an advantage when negotiating with the Naps before the 1907 season, and the club agreed to pay him $4,000 (equivalent to $138,000 in 2025).
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He later also wrote for the *Cleveland Press* and covered the World Series for the *News-Bee* and *Press* from 1907 to 1909.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The *Press* introduced Joss in columns this way: "Of all the baseball players in the land, Addie Joss is far and away the best qualified for this work.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] During the 1908–1909 offseasons, Joss worked on designing an electric scoreboard that would later be known as the Joss Indicator.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The Naps decided to install the scoreboard, which allowed spectators to monitor balls and strikes at League Park.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss attended spring training with Cleveland before the start of the 1911 season.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He collapsed on the field from heat prostration on April 3 in an exhibition game in Chattanooga, Tennessee.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He was taken to a local hospital and released the next day.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] As early as April 7, press reports had taken note of his ill health, but speculated about "ptomaine poisoning" or "nervous indigestion." The Naps traveled to Toledo for exhibition games on April 10 and Joss went to his home on Fulton Street where he was seen by his personal physician, Dr.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Chapman thought Joss could be suffering from nervous indigestion or food poisoning.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] By April 9, as Joss was coughing more and had a severe headache, Chapman changed his diagnosis to pleurisy and reported that Joss would not be able to play for one month and would need ten days of rest to recover.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss could not stand on his own and his speech was slurred.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss was well-liked by his peers and baseball fans.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Upon hearing of his death, the *Press* wrote "every train brings flowers" and "floral tributes by the wagonload are hourly arriving at the Joss home from all sections of the country." His family arranged for the funeral to take place on April 17.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] On that day, the Naps were to face the Detroit Tigers.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Naps players signed a petition stating that they would not attend the game so they could instead attend the funeral.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] They asked for the game to be rescheduled, but the Tigers balked at the request.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] American League president Ban Johnson initially supported the Tigers' position, but he ultimately sided with the Naps.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Naps owner Charles Somers and 15 Naps players attended the funeral, which was officiated by player-turned-evangelist Billy Sunday.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The first "all-star" game was played as a benefit for Joss's family on July 24, 1911.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The Naps invited players from the other seven American League teams to play against them.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Visiting club players who were involved in the game included Home Run Baker, Ty Cobb, Eddie Collins, Sam Crawford, Walter Johnson, Tris Speaker, Gabby Street, and Smoky Joe Wood.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] "I'll do anything they want for Addie Joss' family", Johnson said.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Washington Senators manager Jimmy McAleer volunteered to manage the all-stars.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] "The memory of Addie Joss is sacred to everyone with whom he ever came in contact.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The man never wore a uniform who was a greater credit to the sport than he", McAleer said.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] The game was attended by approximately 15,270 fans and raised nearly $13,000 ($449,000 today) to help Joss' family members pay remaining medical bills.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] In 1981, Lawrence Ritter and Donald Honig included him in their book *The 100 Greatest Baseball Players of All Time.* They described what they called "the Smoky Joe Wood Syndrome", where a player of truly exceptional talent has a career curtailed by injury or illness.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] They argued that such a player should still be included among the greatest all-time players, in spite of career statistics that would not quantitatively rank him with the all-time greats.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] They believed that Joss' career ERA was proof enough of his greatness to be included.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] Joss was inducted into the Cleveland Guardians Hall of Fame on July 29, 2006.
[src:manager-baseball/addie-joss] He was inducted in the same class as Ray Chapman, Rocky Colavito, Al López, Sam McDowell, Al Rosen and Herb Score.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré made his MLB debut with the Dodgers in 1998 at age 19.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He led the majors with 48 home runs with the Dodgers in 2004, was the team MVP of the Red Sox in 2010, played in the 2011 World Series for the Rangers, and tied for the major league lead in hits in 2013.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On September 19, 2014, Beltré surpassed Vladimir Guerrero as the all-time MLB leader for hits by a Dominican player, a record since broken by Albert Pujols in 2019.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 30, 2017, Beltré became the 31st player in MLB history to reach 3,000 hits and the first Dominican player to achieve that milestone.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré retired following the 2018 season with 3,166 career hits (most by a third baseman in MLB history), 477 home runs, and 1,707 runs batted in.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He hit for the cycle three times in his career, in 2008, 2012, and 2015, one of five players to do so in MLB history, the others being Bob Meusel, Babe Herman, Trea Turner, and Christian Yelich.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Having played 21 major league seasons and won the Gold Glove Award five times, Beltré is notable for his defensive prowess and career longevity as well as his power hitting.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He played in four MLB All-Star Games and won the Silver Slugger Award four times.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Upon his retirement, Beltré was the only third baseman in history with both 3,000 career hits and 400 home runs.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] According to Baseball Reference, Beltré has the third-highest Wins Above Replacement among third basemen.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He retired as the all-time leader amongst third basemen in hits and RBIs, and ranked third in home runs amongst third basemen.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He is also the fifth major-leaguer to have hit at least 100 home runs for three different teams.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2024, Beltré was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in his first year of eligibility.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was born on April 7, 1979, in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He attended Liceo Máximo Gómez High School.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] While working out at Campo Las Palmas in 1994, a Los Angeles Dodgers facility — one of the first of its kind for a Major League Baseball (MLB) team in the Dominican Republic — Beltré was spotted by scouts Ralph Avila and Pablo Peguero.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Though only 15 years old and weighing 130 lb (59 kg), Beltré featured a quick swing and live throwing arm.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On the insistence of Avila and Peguero, the Dodgers signed him in July 1994 with a $23,000 signing bonus.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was a highly touted prospect when he began his major league career.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] After being called up to the majors from the then-Dodgers' Double-A affiliate San Antonio Missions, Beltré made his major league debut on June 24, 1998, starting at third base in the first game of an interleague series against the Anaheim Angels.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] At the time, he was the youngest player in the National League (NL).
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] During his first at-bat, Beltré hit a two-out run batted in (RBI) double off Angels starter Chuck Finley into left field to score Paul Konerko from second base to tie the game.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré hit his first home run six days later against Texas Rangers starter Rick Helling.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] At the end of the 1998 season, Beltré finished with 13 errors at third base while batting .215 with seven home runs.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] At one point in the spring training prior to the start of the 1999 season, Beltré's agent, Scott Boras, commented to him that "he couldn't believe" his relatively rapid ascent to the majors and handling of "such a difficult position like third base" at age 20.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré replied that he was 19 years old, not 20.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Boras then realized that Beltré's date of birth in the Dodgers' records was incorrect and indicated the same to the team, but, that if they were to correct the mistake by compensating Beltré for signing him at younger than MLB's allowable age, they would no longer pursue the issue.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Team personnel at Las Palmas denied Boras' assertion.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] As a result, Boras and Beltré went public.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Boras convinced MLB commissioner Bud Selig to investigate the Dodgers, and MLB suspended their scouting operations in the Dominican Republic for one year, as well as Avila and Peguero.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Dodgers general manager Fred Claire, whom MLB did not contact during their investigation, publicly expressed surprise and that he was unaware of the incident.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Selig awarded Beltré $48,500 in damages.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2004, Beltré had a breakout season in which he established a number of career highs, including leading MLB with 48 home runs.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Other career highs included batting .334, 200 hits, 121 RBI, 104 runs scored, .629 slugging percentage, and a then-career high 32 doubles.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He finished second in voting for the NL Most Valuable Player Award (MVP) and was honored with his first career Silver Slugger Award and the Babe Ruth Home Run Award.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] The Seattle Mariners signed Beltré as a free agent before the 2005 season to a five-year, $64 million deal.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Regressing to his pre-2004 form, he batted just .255 with 19 home runs and 87 RBI.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Manager Mike Hargrove said after the season that he thought Beltré was personally disappointed in his first season in Seattle.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] After Beltré batted .167 through April 10, Ted Miller of the *Seattle Post-Intelligencer* wrote that he might become one of the Mariners' greatest busts.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He hit his first home run on April 29, raising his average to .198, and continued to improve his performance, batting .281 with 24 home runs the rest of the season.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 23, against the Boston Red Sox, Beltré hit an inside-the-park home run, the first one ever in Safeco Field history.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Though it was not a great season for Beltré, it was statistically his best as a Mariner.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He hit .276 and had 26 home runs, 99 RBI, and 41 doubles.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also won a Fielding Bible Award for being the top MLB defensive third baseman during the year.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Despite many miscues, Beltré received recognition for his defense in 2007.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He tied with Brandon Inge for the AL lead in errors by a third baseman, with 18, but ranked second in the league in assists, total chances, and range factor.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He had the lowest fielding percentage of all third basemen in the league at .958.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In spite of leading third basemen in errors, Beltré won his first Gold Glove Award, becoming the first Mariners third baseman to win the award.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He won his second consecutive Fielding Bible Award, as well.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On September 1, Beltré hit for the cycle, becoming the fourth Mariner to do so.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Arizona Diamondbacks shortstop Stephen Drew hit for the cycle that day as well, the first time two players had done so since 1920.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré's decision not to wear a cup despite playing third base has been well-documented.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] This came back to hurt him on August 12, 2009, when he took a hard ground ball to the groin.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Although he stayed in for the remainder of the 14-inning victory, he was put on the 15-day disabled list (DL) after suffering bleeding in one of his testicles.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In his first game after returning from the DL, teammate Ken Griffey Jr. conspired with those responsible for the Safeco Field public address system to have Beltré's walk up music be the opening march from *The Nutcracker Suite*.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré declared free agency on November 5, 2009.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On January 7, 2010, Beltré signed a one-year, $9 million deal with the Boston Red Sox.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] The contract had a $5 million player option for 2011 with a $1 million buyout.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] While Beltré's career before coming to the Red Sox had been regarded as somewhat disappointing, he hit .321 with 28 homers and 49 doubles in 2010, benefiting from the hitter-friendly Fenway Park.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré led the Red Sox in batting average and tied David Ortiz for the team lead in RBIs (102).
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré led the Majors in doubles with 49 (also a career-high).
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also finished fourth in the AL in batting average, and was fifth in the AL in total bases (326) and slugging percentage (.553).
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also had two stolen bases on the year, and finished ninth in the MVP voting.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On January 5, 2011, Beltré signed a five-year, $80 million contract with the Texas Rangers.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He played with the Rangers for eight years until his retirement in 2018.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré's statistics improved when he was in his thirties.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] While he had previously played in pitcher-friendly ballparks in Los Angeles and Seattle, the Rangers' ballpark was known as a hitter-friendly environment.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] *The Wall Street Journal* described Beltré's Rangers tenure as "nothing short of brilliant".
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was on the 2011 American League All-Star team.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 22, Beltré strained his hamstring and was also placed on the DL.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On September 4, he singled to right for his 2,000th career hit.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On September 11, Beltré hit two home runs, including the 300th of his career, against the Oakland Athletics.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He was named the AL Player of the Month for September.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2011, Beltré batted .296 with 32 home runs, fifth in the AL.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He was third in the American League in slugging percentage (.561), sixth in RBIs (105), and ninth in OPS (.892).
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] The Fielding Bible said he saved 17 runs on defense in 2011.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On October 4, in Game 4 of the ALDS against the Tampa Bay Rays, Beltré became the sixth player to hit three home runs in a playoff game and the first do so in a Division Series.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré played in the World Series with the Rangers.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He added a fourth playoff home run in Game 5 of the World Series when he went down to one knee chasing an outside curve ball from Chris Carpenter.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Louis Cardinals defeated the Rangers in seven games.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] More recognition was bestowed on Beltré for his defense.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On November 1, he was honored with his third Gold Glove Award and first by a Ranger third baseman since Buddy Bell's six-year run from 1979 to 1984.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also won his third Fielding Bible Award.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On November 2, he was awarded the Silver Slugger Award.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was once again voted on to the All-Star Game starter, along with teammates Josh Hamilton and Mike Napoli.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] It was Beltré's third consecutive All-Star Game and the third of his career.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On August 22, against the Baltimore Orioles, Beltré hit three home runs in his first three at-bats, including two in the same inning.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He joined Pablo Sandoval, Albert Pujols, George Brett, Reggie Jackson, and Babe Ruth as the only players to hit a three-homer game in both the regular season and the postseason.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On August 24, he hit for the cycle for the second time in his career.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Both of his cycles came at Rangers Ballpark.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] With his first coming as a member of the Mariners, it was the first time in MLB history that a player had hit for the cycle more than once at the same stadium.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He joined Joe DiMaggio as the only players in big league history to have a three-homer game and a cycle in the same week.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] For his efforts, Beltré was named the AL Player of the Week for August 20–26.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] During the week, he hit .433 (13-for-30) with three doubles, one triple, five home runs, nine RBI, and seven runs scored.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He had the highest slugging percentage (1.100) in the majors, the most total bases (33), was tied for first in hits and home runs, and tied for second in RBI.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] After the season, Beltré won more defensive accolades.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He won his second consecutive Fielding Bible Award and fourth overall.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He was won a Gold Glove Award and his second Platinum Glove Award.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Wilson Sporting Goods honored him as one of their Defensive Players of the Year in the first year of that award.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] The Rangers organization named Beltré the team captain in 2013.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was named the AL Player of the Week for July 1–7.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He batted .478 (11-for-23) with four home runs, two doubles and five RBI in six games.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He led the American League in home runs, slugging (1.087), OPS (1.607), total bases (25), and extra-base hits (six) while producing the fourth-highest batting average.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré hit safely in all six games with two or more hits four times.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He had the 24th multi-homer game of his career with a pair of home runs on July 4 against Seattle.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Maintaining his strong hitting throughout July, Beltré was named the AL Player of the Month, his fourth career monthly award.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He batted .369 with four doubles, nine homers, 19 RBI, and 13 runs scored over 26 games.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He tied for the major league monthly lead in home runs with Alfonso Soriano and total bases with Torii Hunter (69).
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré also was among the AL leaders in slugging percentage (second, .670), hits (tied for second, 38), extra-base hits (tied for fourth, 13), RBI (tied for fifth) and batting average (sixth).
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He capped off the month with a walk-off home run to lead the Rangers past the Angels on July 31, the seventh walk-off home run of his career and first with Texas.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] It was his third monthly award with Texas, making him one of seven players to win multiple times with the Rangers, including Josh Hamilton (four), Rafael Palmeiro, Alex Rodriguez (both with three), Iván Rodríguez, Juan González and Rubén Sierra (two each).
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] For the season, Beltré played in 161 games and totaled a .315 average, 30 homers, 92 RBI and .509 slugging percentage.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He led the AL with 199 hits and was fourth in batting average and fifth in total bases (321).
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also made the top-10 in games played, slugging percentage and home runs.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In the AL MVP voting, he was tied for seventh place.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] The Dallas-Fort Worth chapter of the Baseball Writers' Association of America named Beltré the Texas Rangers Player of the Year.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On May 7, while facing Jorge de la Rosa of the Colorado Rockies, Beltré hit his 100th home run as a member of the Rangers, becoming the fifth player in major league history to hit 100 home runs with three teams, following Darrell Evans, Reggie Jackson, Alex Rodriguez, and Jim Thome.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On June 24, Beltré singled off Drew Smyly of the Detroit Tigers for his 2,500th career hit and the first hit of a 4-for-4 game.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On September 18, Beltré singled off Sonny Gray in the first inning for his 2,591st hit, surpassing Vladimir Guerrero as the all-time hit leader among Dominican-born players.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré finished the 2014 season batting .324, his highest average since 2004, with 19 home runs and 77 RBI in 148 games.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In February, the Rangers picked up Beltré's option, which would have become guaranteed if he had reached 586 plate appearances in the 2015 season.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] While playing against Cleveland on May 15, Beltré hit his 400th home run on a sinker from Bruce Chen.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He became the 52nd player in MLB history to reach that plateau, and the fourth to do so while playing at least 75 percent of his games at third base.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On August 3, Beltré hit for the cycle with hits in each of the first, second, third, and fifth innings at home against the Houston Astros in a 12–9 win.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] It was his third career cycle, second as a Ranger, and third at the Rangers' home park, making him the only player ever to hit three cycles in one stadium.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He became the first Rangers player to hit for multiple cycles.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] The first player in 82 years to hit for a third cycle, he became the fourth player to do so and tied the major league record for total career cycles, joining Long John Reilly, Bob Meusel, and Babe Herman.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] During the last week of the season, and the Rangers' run towards the AL West championship, Beltré batted .448 with two home runs and 13 RBI.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also went 2-for-4 with a home in the final game of the season to help the Rangers advance to their sixth AL West title.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He finished the season with 18 home runs, 83 RBI, 163 hits, and .287 average.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Enduring a torn ligament in his left thumb over the last three months of the season, Beltré had surgery to repair it immediately after the season ended.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] The Phi Delta Theta fraternity presented Beltré with the 2014 Lou Gehrig Memorial Award on September 17, 2015, making him the first Rangers player to win the award.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On April 15, Beltré and the Rangers agreed to a two-year, $36 million contract extension that would last through the 2018 seasons.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] The extension prevented Beltré from becoming a free agent at the end of the season.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Displaying a drop to one knee, Beltré hit a home run on a curve ball from Jesse Hahn of Oakland on May 17.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In a May 29 game against the Pittsburgh Pirates, Beltré hit a two-run home run off Juan Nicasio to give him 1,501 career RBI, making him the 54th player to reach the milestone and the fourth third baseman.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 2, Beltré became the 28th player all time to amass 10,000 career at-bats.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 23, he became the 36th player all time to record 11,000 career plate appearances.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Two days later, he hit a walk-off home run, the ninth of his career, against the Athletics in the bottom of the ninth inning for a 7−6 win.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On August 24, Beltré, in a game against the Cincinnati Reds, hit a go-ahead two-out double for his 2,900th career hit and led the Rangers to a 6–5 win.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] With this hit, Beltré became the 39th player in major league history to reach the milestone.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré would once again show his signature home run knee drop after hitting a solo shot in the second inning in a game against the Houston Astros on September 13.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] His 30th of the season, it was the first time he reached the mark since 2013 and fifth in his career.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Ten days later, his two-run home run in the eighth inning against the Athletics aided the Rangers in clinching the AL West division crown for the second year in a row and the seventh in franchise history.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also reached 100 RBI for the first time since 2012 and fifth time in his career.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He won the Gold Glove at third base, the fifth of his career.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré began the 2017 season on the 10-day disabled list after injuring his right leg near the end of spring training.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 4, Beltré hit his 600th career double, becoming the 17th player all-time to reach that milestone.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 7, Beltré became the 21st player to amass 5,000 career total bases.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 26, Beltré was ejected by umpire Gerry Davis; in a game against the Miami Marlins, Davis asked Beltré, who was the next scheduled batter, to move closer to the on-deck circle.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré responded by picking up the edge of the logo that marked the on-deck circle and moving it closer to where he had been standing, which prompted Davis to eject him.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré collected his 3,000th hit with a double into left field against Wade Miley of the Baltimore Orioles on July 30, making him the 31st player to reach this milestone and the first Dominican-born player to accomplish it.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré played in only 94 games in 2017 due to hamstring and calf problems.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Prior to the start of the 2018 season, the Rangers signed Bartolo Colón, giving them the only two active players with at least 20 seasons in the major leagues and the last two active players to have played in 1990s.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On April 5, Beltré doubled in the second inning versus the Oakland Athletics to pass Rod Carew as the all-time Latin American hits leader.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On June 13, Beltré hit a double that gave him 3,090 career hits; this made him the all-time leader in hits by a player not born in the United States, surpassing former Mariners teammate Ichiro Suzuki.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On November 20, 2018, Beltré announced his retirement.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2,933 games over 21 seasons, Beltré posted a .286 batting average with 3,166 hits, 477 home runs, 1,707 RBI, 121 stolen bases, 1,524 runs, 636 doubles, a .339 on-base percentage, a .480 slugging percentage, and a .960 fielding percentage.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 28 postseason games, he hit .261 with five home runs and 11 RBI.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré is regarded as one of the greatest third basemen of all time.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Having played 21 major league seasons and won five Gold Gloves, he was notable for his longevity, fielding ability, and power hitting.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré's signature home run swing included a drop to one knee when connecting with a breaking ball, particularly notable during Game 5 of the 2011 World Series against Cardinals ace Chris Carpenter.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré's defensive style was somewhat unorthodox.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Rangers manager Ron Washington remarked that Beltré fielded ground balls incorrectly by stopping before catching the ball and relying very little on the positioning of his feet in throwing the ball to first base.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré explained that his arm was so strong that early in his career he was making many throwing errors; by planting his feet, he was able to improve his accuracy despite his lack of proper foot positioning.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Another major league manager, Joe Maddon, compared the unique style of Beltré's defensive play to Ozzie Smith's "flair at shortstop", Stan Musial's "coiled batting stance", and the way Steve Carlton wrapped his left wrist before releasing a slider.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Commented Maddon further on Beltré's defense, "There's a lot of guys that did things unique to them that weren't out of the *Spalding Guide*.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He's a super smart player, knows where to position himself." Beltré was known for the sense of playfulness and joy that he exhibited on the field.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He had a routine with Rangers shortstop Elvis Andrus on pop flies where both men put their arms up to catch the ball.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] During a game against the Red Sox on June 26, 2016, Sandy León hit a foul ball which landed in the first row in the stands, just out of Beltré's reach.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] However, instead of returning immediately to the infield, he reached very close to the ball in a motion, pretending as if he were going to take it away from the fan who caught León's foul ball.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] As a hitter, Beltré also regularly pointed to the first base umpire to appeal a checked swing, a move usually only done by catchers.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré also had a joking relationship with Mariners pitcher Felix Hernández, which included Beltré getting ejected in 2010, when the two former teammates first faced each other, and Hernández hugging Beltré on the field in 2017, the day after Beltré's 3,000th major league hit.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was also known for his dislike of anyone touching the top of his head.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Before the game where he recorded his 3,000th hit, he let his teammates touch his head.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Much to his dismay, the act turned into a game, inducing repeat offenders, including Andrus.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] After a game in which he hit a grand slam that provided the decisive runs in a 5–2 win over the Athletics on August 15, 2016, he took a broom from the groundskeepers closet and began combing an area of infield dirt.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Still, Rougned Odor trotted to Beltré carrying a full drink bucket but missed drenching Beltré when he threw the blue sports drink at his teammate.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré played for the Dominican Republic in the 2006 World Baseball Classic (WBC).
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He was named to the All-WBC team after hitting 4 home runs in six games.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also played in the 2017 WBC, batting 1-for-15 in four games.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2017, he was dealing with leg injuries that caused him to miss the beginning of the MLB season.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was one of several Dominican Hall of Famers assisting general manager Nelson Cruz ahead of the 2026 WBC.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] On June 5, 2023, Beltré was named the honorary general manager for the Karachi Monarchs of the Baseball United league for their inaugural season.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré served as the manager for the American League team in the 2024 All-Star Futures Game.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré has contributed to humanitarian activities in the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex such as the Texas Rangers Baseball Foundation, Texas Rangers RBI program, the I Love Baseball program, which operates in the Dominican Republic, and the Baseball Tomorrow Fund.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] He has donated to Dave Valle's Esperanza International as well as foundations established by other major-league players, including Robinson Chirinos, Eddie Guardado, Joakim Soria, and Michael Young.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2021, Beltré helped pay to reconstruct a baseball stadium in the Dominican Republic where he grew up playing.
[src:manager-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré and his wife have three children.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick was known for a strong voice and for booming strike calls.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] After he left active umpiring in 1971, Barlick became an umpire scout and supervisor.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1989.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick was born in Springfield, Illinois.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] His father, an Austrian immigrant, worked for 50 years at a Peabody coal mine.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick dropped out of high school after two years to support his family.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He joined the Civilian Conservation Corps, and spent six months in Washington and six months in Wisconsin.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] When Barlick's brother died, he returned to the coal mine to assist his father.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick said that he did not play much baseball as a youngster, but that he often watched the game.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] During a coal mine strike, a 19-year-old Barlick was offered $1 ($24) to umpire his first game.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He played outfield in semi-pro baseball, but he was described as "mediocre." In August 1936, the Class-D Northeast Arkansas League, in need of a replacement umpire, hired Barlick for the last four weeks of the season.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] In 1937, Barlick was hired by the Class-B Piedmont League, moved to the Eastern League in 1939, and was promoted to the International League later that season.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Late in the 1940 season, NL umpire Bill Klem was unable to work due to an ankle injury, so Barlick was hired as a replacement.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He made his debut in a doubleheader at Shibe Park on September 8.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick was offered a contract for the 1941 season, and was 26 years old at the start of the season, making him one of the youngest MLB umpires in history.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Before the 1941 season, Klem had strongly endorsed Barlick, saying, "He's going to be the greatest umpire in baseball history.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He has a love of his work, a pride in it and the physical qualifications.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick made his first ejection on July 27 of that year, when Brooklyn Dodgers catcher Herman Franks objected to Barlick's strike zone.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick was selected as an umpire for the 1942 All-Star Game at the Polo Grounds.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick joined the Coast Guard in November 1943, during World War II.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He spent most of the next two years assigned to an 83-foot cutter based at the Coast Guard Academy in New London, Connecticut.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He was discharged in 1945, having earned the rank of Seaman First Class.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick returned to umpiring in 1946, when he umpired his first World Series.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Klem repeated his endorsement of Barlick that year.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] "There's a fellow who's going to be one of the great all-time umpires.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He's got everything and knows how to handle himself.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Before I saw him, I predicted he'd be a great umpire just from what I heard about him." In 1947, Barlick was the first base umpire during Jackie Robinson's MLB debut.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] In 1949, Barlick was again chosen as an umpire for the 1949 All-Star Game.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He began the game at home plate, although when it became time for the umpires to rotate, as was customary during All-Star games, Barlick left the game, leaving the right field line uncovered; no reason was given for his departure.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] In August 1949, Barlick ruled a forfeit at Shibe Park in a game between the Philadelphia Phillies and New York Giants.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Fans had become irate over a call made by Barlick's crew member George Barr, and they littered the field with fruit, soda bottles and paper.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] The ruling constituted the first major league forfeit since 1942.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Before the 1956 season, Barlick was hospitalized in Illinois for treatment of a heart problem.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] League president Warren Giles characterized the issue as a minor heart ailment, but newspaper reports held that Barlick would not be ready for opening day that year.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] After he sat out the entire 1956 season, a March 1957 article reported that the heart issue would probably cause him to miss that season as well.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He returned to the field for the 1958 season.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] In 1961, the *Sporting News* polled managers and coaches to determine the best umpires in the major leagues.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick was voted as the most respected umpire in the National League, as well as the best caller of balls and strikes, best on the bases, best knowledge of rules, best at being in the right position and most serious-minded.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick stated that the poll was a disgrace due to the lack of qualifications of the writers and the nature of the categories, which included "most sarcastic", "hardest to talk to", "biggest grandstander", and "worst pop-off".
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] In 1963, the league instructed umpires to crack down on balks by pitchers.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] After the 1963 season, Barlick took a job as a public relations representative at Springfield's City Water, Light & Power utility.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] However, he returned as an umpire for the 1964 season.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick's crew worked the first game at the Houston Astrodome in 1965.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] In 1966, Barlick missed nine games after his mother, Louise, died in Springfield.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He missed the last two weeks of the 1966 season due to high blood pressure.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] After the 1968 season, Barlick accompanied the St.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Louis Cardinals on a five-week tour of Japan.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] In 1969, Barlick was the crew chief for the first-ever National League Championship Series.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] In late 1970, he umpired the final game at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh as well as the first game at Riverfront Stadium in Cincinnati.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] In 1971, Barlick was awarded the Umpire of the Year Award at the Al Somers Umpire School, which was based on a poll of other MLB umpires.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He stated that the award was "very special," and that it was "a true, honorable, sincere award because it is given to an umpire by umpires." The 1971 season was Barlick's final year of umpiring, and he skipped the final series of the season at the advice of his fellow umpires.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick had been known for his very loud calls behind home plate.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Subsequent MLB officials, including Dusty Boggess and Dutch Rennert, said that they tried to imitate him when they became umpires.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] After retiring from umpiring, Barlick was hired by the league to supervise and scout umpires, a job he held for 22 years.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] When the umpires went on strike at the conclusion of the 1984 regular season, Barlick and fellow supervisor Ed Vargo were located in the dugouts during the playoffs to assist the replacement umpires with questions over rules.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] In 1989, he was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame by the Veterans Committee.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Manager Leo Durocher and umpire Bill McGowan were also considered by the committee that year, but the group could only vote in one non-player per year.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick had been under consideration by the committee for several years before his election.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] Barlick wore uniform number 1 when the NL adopted them for its umpires in 1970; however, the league retired number 3 in Barlick's honor after his induction into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1989.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] On December 27, 1995, Barlick collapsed at his home.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] He was taken to Memorial Medical Center in Springfield, where he died.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] His wife, Jennie, and two children survived him.
[src:manager-baseball/al-barlick] In 2013, the Bob Feller Act of Valor Award honored Barlick as one of 37 Baseball Hall of Fame members for his service in the Coast Guard during World War II.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] In baseball, the **field manager** (commonly referred to as the **manager**) is the equivalent of a head coach who is responsible for overseeing and making final decisions on all aspects of on-field team strategy, lineup selection, training and instruction.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] Managers are typically assisted by a staff of assistant coaches whose responsibilities are specialized.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] Field managers are typically not involved in off-field personnel decisions or long-term club planning, responsibilities that are instead held by a team's general manager.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] The manager chooses the batting order and starting pitcher before each game, and makes substitutions throughout the game – among the most significant being those decisions regarding when to bring in a relief pitcher.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] How much control a manager takes in a game's strategy varies from manager to manager and from game to game.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] Some managers control pitch selection, defensive positioning, decisions to bunt, steal, pitch out, etc., while others designate an assistant coach or a player (often the catcher) to make some or all of these decisions.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] Some managers choose to act as their team's first base or third base coach while their team is batting in order to more closely communicate with baserunners, but most managers delegate this responsibility to an assistant.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] In many cases, a manager is a former professional, semi-professional or college player.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] From 1901 to 1981, 21% of MLB managers had played catcher during their playing career--the most common.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] Outfielders made up 16.6% and second basemen made up 13% of managers.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] Over the same period, managers who were second basemen had the highest winning percentage.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] The manager's responsibilities normally are limited to in-game decisions, with off-field roster management and personnel decisions falling to the team's general manager.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] The term *manager* used without qualification almost always refers to the field manager (essentially equivalent to the head coach in other North American professional sports leagues), while the general manager is often called the GM.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] This usage dates back to the early days of professional baseball when it was common practice for teams to have just one "manager" on their staff, and where GM duties were performed either by the field manager or (more commonly) by the owner of the team.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] Some owners (most famously, Connie Mack of the Philadelphia Athletics) carried out both GM and field managerial duties themselves.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] Major League Baseball managers differ from the head coaches of most other professional sports in that they dress in the same uniform as the players and are assigned a jersey number.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] The wearing of a matching uniform is frequently practiced at other levels of play, as well.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] The manager may be called "skipper" or "skip" informally by his players.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] There have been 24 people who have been elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum primarily for their careers as managers.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] Of the 24 Hall of Fame managers, 20 were Major League players before becoming managers (the exceptions being Jim Leyland, Joe McCarthy, Frank Selee, and Earl Weaver).
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] The most recent manager to be elected was Leyland, who was elected to the Hall of Fame by the Contemporary Baseball Era Committee in 2024.
[src:manager-baseball/manager-baseball] were the first managers to be elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1937.
